import statsmodels.api as sm
import numpy as np

df_clean = df.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan).dropna(subset=['Elo', 'CP', 'Ply','Difficulty'])

df_clean_w = df_clean[df_clean.Side=='W']
df_clean_b = df_clean[df_clean.Side=='B']

# Prepare the data
X = df_clean_w[['Elo', 'CP', 'Ply','Difficulty']]
X = sm.add_constant(X)  # Add a constant (intercept)
y = df_clean_w['Result_num']

# Fit the logistic regression model
logit_model = sm.Logit(y, X)
result_w = logit_model.fit()

# Print the summary of the model
print(result_w.summary())

df_clean_w['exp_win'] = result_w.predict(X)

# Assuming df_clean_w is your full sample data

# Plot the Lowess curve for Elo > 2000 without scatter points

            scatter=False, lowess=True, line_kws={"color": "red"})
plt.plot([], [], color='red', label='Elo > 2000')  # Manually add the label for the legend

# Plot the Lowess curve for Elo < 1200 without scatter points
sns.regplot(x='CP', y='exp_win', data=df_clean_w[df_clean_w.Elo < 1200], 
            scatter=False, lowess=True, line_kws={"color": "blue"})

plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.yticks(np.arange(0, 1.1, 0.1))

# Add a grey dotted line at y=0.5

plt.ylabel('Expected Win')
plt.title('Expected Win vs CP for Different Elo Ranges')

# Create the legend to differentiate between the curves
plt.legend()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have the sampled data, replace this with your actual data
# Simulating some example data for demonstration purposes
np.random.seed(42)
CP = np.linspace(1, 100, 500)  # Replace with your actual 'CP' data
exp_win = 0.01 * CP**2 - 0.5 * CP + np.random.normal(0, 50, 500)  # Replace with your actual 'exp_win' data

# Perform a linear fit
slope, intercept = np.polyfit(CP, exp_win, 1)

# Perform a quadratic fit (degree 2)
coefficients_quad = np.polyfit(CP, exp_win, 2)


# Plot the linear fit
plt.plot(CP, slope * CP + intercept, color='red', label=f'Linear Fit: y = {slope:.2f}x + {intercept:.2f}')

# Plot the quadratic fit
plt.plot(CP, np.polyval(coefficients_quad, CP), color='green', label=f'Quadratic Fit')



plt.xlabel('CP')
plt.ylabel('Expected Win')
plt.title('Curve Fits on Expected Win vs CP')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
